      Central crypto
   =20
 =20

Imagine that you are a financial regulator, and consider the general propos=
ition:
=09There is some crypto entity, some company that does something=C2=A0in th=
e crypto industry.=09Regular people give it their dollars or crypto for som=
e purpose.=09It gives them back some sort of crypto receipt, saying =E2=80=
=9Cwe owe you one dollar=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe owe you one crypto=E2=80=
=9D or whatever.

At a very high level of generality, what do you think about that? What I wo=
uld say is:
=09In 2013,=C2=A0you probably thought =E2=80=9Cah, yes, this entity is doin=
g a fraud, and plans to steal the money or crypto.=E2=80=9D But (1) you did=
n=E2=80=99t think about it that=C2=A0much, since these entities tended to b=
e small and cater to a small niche of crypto enthusiasts,=C2=A0and (2) it i=
s not like the crypto entity was coming to your office to have meetings wit=
h you.=09In 2021, you probably thought =E2=80=9Cah, yes, innovation, let us=
 work with this crypto entity to build the future of finance on the blockch=
ain.=E2=80=9D Unless you were the US Securities and Exchange Commission; th=
ey never really thought that. But otherwise. The New York Department of Fin=
ancial Services was  out issuing =E2=80=9CBitLicenses=E2=80=9D to crypto en=
tities. Crypto entities were regularly walking into your office, accompanie=
d by reputable high-powered lawyers who probably used to work at your offic=
e, with suggestions for how you should best regulate crypto. They seemed ni=
ce and earnest, and you took their suggestions seriously.=09In 2023, you pr=
obably think =E2=80=9Cah, yes, this entity is doing a fraud, and plans to s=
teal the money or crypto.=E2=80=9D

Look around! Voyager Digital Ltd. is a crypto entity that is based in New Y=
ork and was  publicly traded on the Toronto Stock Exchange; it took custome=
rs=E2=80=99 money, promised them interest, and then lost the money, shut do=
wn withdrawals and  went bankrupt in July. Gemini Trust Co. is a New York r=
egulated crypto entity that ran lots of ads about how =E2=80=9Cthe revoluti=
on needs rules=E2=80=9D; it took customers=E2=80=99 money, promised them in=
terest, and then=C2=A0loaned=C2=A0the money to Genesis Global Capital LLC, =
which lost it; Gemini=C2=A0 shut down=C2=A0withdrawals from its Earn produc=
t in November and is now trying to get the money back in  Genesis=E2=80=99s=
 bankruptcy. FTX Trading Ltd. is a crypto entity whose founder, Sam Bankman=
-Fried, appeared regularly on stage with politicians and regulators and tes=
tified before Congress about how to improve crypto regulation; FTX took cus=
tomers=E2=80=99 money, loaned it to its affiliates,   lost it, shut down wi=
thdrawals and filed for bankruptcy in November; Bankman-Fried was arrested,=
   accused of fraud.
I submit to you that the main fact of crypto regulation in early 2023 is th=
at regulators feel really burned by the events of 2022, and particularly by=
 the collapse of FTX. =E2=80=9CWe want to work with these nice smart young =
people who are building the financial system of the future, and I am sure t=
hat with their advice we can write=C2=A0smart regulations=C2=A0that protect=
=C2=A0consumers while still fostering innovation=E2=80=9D was a totally nor=
mal thing for regulators (except the SEC) to think and say in 2021. But now=
 it is not! Now too many of those smart young people are under indictment o=
r giving interviews from undisclosed locations; too much customer money is =
gone. If you run a crypto exchange and you want to set up a meeting with re=
gulators to talk about how to write regulations to prevent a repeat of the =
recent crypto collapses, they will not trust you, because=C2=A0that is what=
 FTX was saying too. There is not much goodwill left.
Meanwhile, in the US, a lot of the=C2=A0law=C2=A0around this stuff is a bit=
 uncertain and debatable. There are long-running boring debates about wheth=
er certain sorts of cryptocurrencies are =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=80=9D subje=
ct to the SEC=E2=80=99s jurisdiction. The SEC   tends to think that almost =
everything in crypto is a security; most crypto companies think that almost=
 nothing is a security. (Very few crypto companies register their token or =
product offerings with the SEC, and the SEC sometimes sues them for doing u=
nregistered securities offerings.) The  general rule =E2=80=94=C2=A0called =
the =E2=80=9CHowey test=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that a security is =E2=
=80=9Cthe investment of money in a common enterprise with a reasonable expe=
ctation of profits to be derived from the efforts of others.=E2=80=9D A lot=
 of crypto projects look a lot like that, but you can debate the specifics.
In 2021, if the SEC thought your token was a security and you thought it wa=
sn=E2=80=99t, you could go to court to argue about it, and try to convince =
a judge that the SEC was wrong on the law. You might win, who knows. (Rippl=
e Labs Inc. is in a court fight with the SEC about whether its XRP token is=
 a security; the SEC sued in 2020, and   a ruling is expected pretty soon.)=
 But in 2023, the SEC can go to court and say to a judge =E2=80=9Cwe need t=
o protect investors from unregistered crypto securities offerings, because=
=C2=A0look at how many of them are frauds that went bankrupt,=E2=80=9D and =
while that=C2=A0legal=C2=A0argument is no better than it was in 2021, it is=
 much more=C2=A0persuasive=C2=A0now.
  [1]
=C2=A0At some emotional level the debate is =E2=80=9Cwe need to stop frauds=
ters=E2=80=9D versus =E2=80=9Cwe need to allow for innovation,=E2=80=9D and=
 the fraud/innovation balance has shifted a lot in recent months.
Anyway, there have been=C2=A0some recent regulatory actions on some crypto =
things, and I will talk about them below, but I want to start with this sor=
t of legal realist point. When crypto is popular and exciting and going up,=
 if you are a regulator who says =E2=80=9Cno, we must stop this,=E2=80=9D y=
ou look like a killjoy. Investors want to put their money into stuff that i=
s going up, and they are mad at you for stopping them. Politicians like the=
 stuff that is going up, and hold hearings about how you=E2=80=99re stiflin=
g innovation. Crypto founders are rich and popular and criticize you on Twi=
tter and get a lot of likes and retweets. Your own regulatory employees, wh=
o have an eye on their next private-sector jobs, want to be leaders in cryp=
to innovation rather than just banning everything.
When crypto is going down and so many projects are evaporating in fraud and=
 bankruptcy, you can kind of say =E2=80=9CI told you so.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Ther=
e is just a lot more appetite to regulate, or I guess just to shut everythi=
ng down. =E2=80=9CYou are stifling innovation,=E2=80=9D the indicted founde=
r of a bankrupt crypto firm can say, but nobody cares.=C2=A0
I guess this is a little bad, in the sense that it would be better for regu=
lators to impose sensible regulations on the way up =E2=80=94=C2=A0before p=
eople lose all their money =E2=80=94=C2=A0rather than being too lax on the =
way up and overreacting after the crash. But it seems hard to avoid. Also t=
he advantage of regulating after the crash is that you have a better sense =
of what the risks are. =E2=80=9CCrypto is decentralized and transparent and=
 avoids the risks of traditional fractional reserve banking, so it doesn=E2=
=80=99t need to be regulated like traditional finance,=E2=80=9D I suppose p=
eople could say in 2021. But now we   know better.

