       =20
  [1] My own view is that the legal argument was always pretty good: Under =
longstanding US law, it sure does seem that most crypto tokens are securiti=
es. But pre-FTX, crypto people could go around saying =E2=80=9Cthe SEC is r=
elying on outdated legal doctrines that don=E2=80=99t fit the innovative mo=
dern crypto economy,=E2=80=9D and that had some appeal; it has so much less=
 appeal now.


  [2] In particular, Ethereum's founders *sold* Ether tokens, before Ethere=
um was live, to finance building out the system. That sounds a whole lot li=
ke a securities offering, and the SEC has   halted very similar offerings i=
n recent years. I suspect if Ethereum did that *today*, instead of in 2014,=
 the SEC would have objections. I once wrote that =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s =
a sense in which this sale=E2=80=94the Ether =E2=80=98pre-mine,=E2=80=99 or=
 =E2=80=98initial coin offering=E2=80=99 (ICO)=E2=80=94was the original sin=
 of crypto as a financing tool,=E2=80=9D and I bet the SEC thinks that too.


  [3] There are also hints that just staking your own Ether doesn=E2=80=99t=
 make Ethereum a security: It=E2=80=99s Kraken=E2=80=99s centralized offeri=
ng of staking as a service that makes this a pooled investment relying on t=
he efforts of others, not the staking rewards themselves. See, e.g., paragr=
aph 39: =E2=80=9CThe Kraken Staking Program has several features that diffe=
rentiate it from staking and earning rewards on your own,=E2=80=9D etc.


  [4] Kraken=E2=80=99s former CEO, Jesse Powell,  tweeted: =E2=80=9COh man,=
 all I had to do was fill out a form on a website and tell people that stak=
ing rewards come from staking? Wish I'd seen this video before paying a $30=
m fine and agreeing to permanently shut down the service in the US. How dum=
b do I look. Gosh.=E2=80=9D


  [5] One weird fact about stablecoins is that they =E2=80=94 and crypto =
=E2=80=94 grew up largely in a low-interest-rate environment, and it is jus=
t sort of the norm that stablecoin issuers do not pay interest. Of course t=
hey *earn* interest =E2=80=94 they keep the dollars in bank accounts or Tre=
asury bills or whatever =E2=80=94 but they don=E2=80=99t pass it on to hold=
ers of the coins; the issuer just keeps the interest. This is weird and luc=
rative but also a good argument against being a security. One possibility i=
s that SEC suspicion of stablecoins will *prevent* stablecoin issuers from =
ever paying interest, making the business more lucrative.


  [6] Actually there is some weirdness around redemption, and it=E2=80=99s =
not obvious that every stablecoin owner is a direct creditor of the issuer.=
 But you are certainly economically exposed to the issuer=E2=80=99s finance=
s if you own its stablecoins.


