/30539045.268773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjItMTItMTMvaG93LXRvLWRvLWZyYXVkLWF0LWEtZnV0dXJlcy1leGNoYW5nZT9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQwMjEzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB0cd7cdc3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  accused of fraud</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I submit to you that the main fact of crypto r=
egulation in early 2023 is that regulators feel really burned by the events=
 of 2022, and particularly by the collapse of FTX. =E2=80=9CWe want to work=
 with these nice smart young people who are building the financial system o=
f the future, and I am sure that with their advice we can write=C2=A0smart =
regulations=C2=A0that protect=C2=A0consumers while still fostering innovati=
on=E2=80=9D was a totally normal thing for regulators (except the SEC) to t=
hink and say in 2021. But now it is not! Now too many of those smart young =
people are under indictment or giving interviews from undisclosed locations=
; too much customer money is gone. If you run a crypto exchange and you wan=
t to set up a meeting with regulators to talk about how to write regulation=
s to prevent a repeat of the recent crypto collapses, they will not trust y=
ou, because=C2=A0<em>that is what FTX was saying too</em>. There is not muc=
h goodwill left.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, in the US, a lot of the=C2=A0<em>la=
w=C2=A0</em>around this stuff is a bit uncertain and debatable. There are l=
ong-running boring debates about whether certain sorts of cryptocurrencies =
are =E2=80=9Csecurities=E2=80=9D subject to the SEC=E2=80=99s jurisdiction.=
 The SEC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30539045.=
268773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDkt=
MDgvZ2FyeS1nZW5zbGVyLXdhbnRzLXRvLXJlZ3VsYXRlLWNyeXB0bz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjEzMjN=
fTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdG=
VybT0yMzAyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17f4=
4d29" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  tends to think</a> that almost everything in crypto is a se=
curity; most crypto companies think that almost nothing is a security. (Ver=
y few crypto companies register their token or product offerings with the S=
EC, and the SEC sometimes sues them for doing unregistered securities offer=
ings.) The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3053904=
5.268773/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9kbHQtZnJhbWV3b3JrLnBkZg/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBed0f74e3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> general rule</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0called=
 the =E2=80=9CHowey test=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that a security is =E2=
=80=9Cthe investment of money in a common enterprise with a reasonable expe=
ctation of profits to be derived from the efforts of others.=E2=80=9D A lot=
 of crypto projects look a lot like that, but you can debate the specifics.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2021, if the SEC thought your token was a s=
ecurity and you thought it wasn=E2=80=99t, you could go to court to argue a=
bout it, and try to convince a judge that the SEC was wrong on the law. You=
 might win, who knows. (Ripple Labs Inc. is in a court fight with the SEC a=
bout whether its XRP token is a security; the SEC sued in 2020, and <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30539045.268773/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTcvZnR4LWNvbGxhcHNl=
LXB1dHMtZm9jdXMtb24tcmlwcGxlLWNhc2UtZm9yLXdoby1zaG91bGQtcmVndWxhdGUtY3J5cHR=
vP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT=
1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB0b1164fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  a ruling is expected pretty soon</a>=
.) But in 2023, the SEC can go to court and say to a judge =E2=80=9Cwe need=
 to protect investors from unregistered crypto securities offerings, becaus=
e=C2=A0<em>look at how many of them are frauds that went bankrupt</em>,=E2=
=80=9D and while that=C2=A0<em>legal=C2=A0</em>argument is no better than i=
t was in 2021, it is much more=C2=A0<em>persuasive=C2=A0</em>now.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0At some emotional level the debate is =E2=80=9Cwe need to stop fr=
audsters=E2=80=9D versus =E2=80=9Cwe need to allow for innovation,=E2=80=9D=
 and the fraud/innovation balance has shifted a lot in recent months.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, there have been=C2=A0some recent regul=
atory actions on some crypto things, and I will talk about them below, but =
I want to start with this sort of legal realist point. When crypto is popul=
ar and exciting and going up, if you are a regulator who says =E2=80=9Cno, =
we must stop this,=E2=80=9D you look like a killjoy. Investors want to put =
their money into stuff that is going up, and they are mad at you for stoppi=
ng them. Politicians like the stuff that is going up, and hold hearings abo=
ut how you=E2=80=99re stifling innovation. Crypto founders are rich and pop=
ular and criticize you on Twitter and get a lot of likes and retweets. Your=
 own regulatory employees, who have an eye on their next private-sector job=
s, want to be leaders in crypto innovation rather than just banning everyth=
ing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When crypto is going down and so many projects=
 are evaporating in fraud and bankruptcy, you can kind of say =E2=80=9CI to=
ld you so.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0There is just a lot more appetite to regulate, or =
I guess just to shut everything down. =E2=80=9CYou are stifling innovation,=
=E2=80=9D the indicted founder of a bankrupt crypto firm can say, but nobod=
y cares.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess this is a little bad, in the sense tha=
t it would be better for regulators to impose sensible regulations on the w=
ay up =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>before</em> people lose all their money =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0rather than being too lax on the way up and overreacting after the cr=
ash. But it seems hard to avoid. Also the advantage of regulating after the=
 crash is that you have a better sense of what the risks are. =E2=80=9CCryp=
to is decentralized and transparent and avoids the risks of traditional fra=
ctional reserve banking, so it doesn=E2=80=99t need to be regulated like tr=
aditional finance,=E2=80=9D I suppose people could say in 2021. But now we =
