bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> global distributed computer system</a>. People can run programs =E2=80=94=
 smart contracts, crypto exchanges, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the Ethereum sys=
tem, which is a sort of virtual computer whose state is maintained by thous=
ands of independent nodes. Anyone can run programs on Ethereum, though you =
have to pay transaction fees =E2=80=94=C2=A0called =E2=80=9Cgas=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0to run your program. The fees are paid in Ether, the currenc=
y of the Ethereum system.=C2=A0There is a system for validating Ethereum tr=
ansactions, for making sure that all the nodes of=C2=A0the distributed virt=
ual computer agree=C2=A0on what programs have been run and what the results=
 were. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30539045.26=
8773/aHR0cHM6Ly9ldGhlcmV1bS5vcmcvZW4vc3Rha2luZy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf=
9a290df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> This system</a> involves people =E2=80=94=C2=A0called =E2=
=80=9Cstakers=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0depositing 32 Ether and then running =
computer programs to validate the transactions. In exchange for doing this,=
 the stakers get paid in Ether; effectively they get a share of the fees th=
at people pay to run programs on the computer that they help maintain.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What does this make Ether? Well, it is a littl=
e bit of a lot of things:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ether is a way to pay for computer ti=
me: You get Ether to pay to run programs on the Ethereum system, or you get=
 paid Ether for running those programs. Ether is like an <em>arcade token</=
em>, or like a Starbucks card or airline miles, a limited-use form of money=
 that can be used to pay for a=C2=A0 particular service. In crypto this ide=
a is called a =E2=80=9Cutility token,=E2=80=9D a cryptocurrency that you ne=
ed to pay to use some crypto project.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">Ether is kind of like <em>money </em>more generally =E2=80=94=C2=A0you =
can use Ether to pay for lots of stuff that is <em>not </em>Ethereum<em> </=
em>transaction fees =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the staking mechanism is a way to=C2=
=A0<em>earn interest on your money</em>. Staking is sort of like a =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0bank account? A bond? But decentralized; the =E2=80=9Cissuer=E2=80=
=9D of the bond is the Ethereum system rather than a particular company.=C2=
=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ether is kind of like=C2=A0<em=
>stock=C2=A0</em>in the Ethereum system. If a lot of people want to use Eth=
ereum to run programs and do stuff, then the value of Ether will go up. And=
 owning Ether sort of gives you =E2=80=94=C2=A0through the staking mechanis=
m =E2=80=94=C2=A0a share of the profits. Sort of.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t want to insist on any of these=
